**Pre-Processing input files**

**Following constraints are assumed**

- The input would be in order
  - _xxx,yyy,zzz,...,_ wmc, dit, noc, cbo, rfc, lcom, ca, ce, npm, lcom3, loc, dam, moa, mfa, cam, ic, cbm, amc, max\_cc, avg\_cc,bug
  - During pre-processing the code is automatically trimming columns not needed. So columns from wmc onwards would be considered.


- Extension of data files is .csv
  - In case the extension is not .csv file, then the files are ignored to handle stray files

**Clustering**

For classification I have used weka classifier libraries. On the basis of input parameter, the code would be clustering file wise for example classifying arc.csv, berek.csv separately (default case) or clubbing all the files and classifying the complete data set at once.

**Demo Steps and Documentation**

Note: I have tested the code in Unix/Linux enviornemnt.

For running the executable, we would need java 8 installed on s system.

And to run, following command needs to be entered:

java -cp dm-one-2017HT12225-1.0-SNAPSHOT-jar-with-dependencies.jar dm.assignment.App &lt;path of csv files&gt; True/False #true means clubbing all files for clustering, false means clustering files one by one

In order to build the code, we need to have [maven](http://www.baeldung.com/install-maven-on-windows-linux-mac). After Maven and Java 8 are installed, we need to run the following command in sources directory:

mvn clean compile assembly:single

This would be creating the jar dm-one-2017HT12225-1.0-SNAPSHOT-jar-with-dependencies.jar for further runs/classifications.



**Basics about different classifiers covered:**

- Decision Tree

A decision tree is a set of the possible outcomes of a series of related choices. They can can be used either to drive informal discussion or to map out an algorithm that predicts the best choice mathematically.

They are easy to understand but may become overly complex in case the input set is very huge

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- K-Mean Clustering

In layman&#39;s terms this method tries to organize n data points into k clusters. With centroid being decided by nearest mean.

- Hierarchical clustering

This clustering methodology tries to group the data set at different levels on the basis of distance. Nearest neighbors are the data sets which are lease distant from each other then along with the other data-points/clusters, it forms a series of observation. On the basis of use case, we can cut the cluster at a specific distance to find smaller clusters

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- Fuzzy c-mean Clustering

It is an evolution over basic k-means clustering, here the data clustering technique groups the dataset into n clusters with every datapoint in the dataset belonging to every cluster to a certain degree.
